summary: thoughts on thor? And what  do you think the best end for Marvel is and their main characters?
question: thoughts on thor? And what  do you think the best end for Marvel is and their main characters?
answer:
Thor’s great! He’s a swell dude who comes from a background of having been messed up and unpleasant in…well, the way the rest of his family is, and having grown beyond the worst of himself now has to deal with the worst of his home, while at heart he’d rather be out there smiting villains and wooing women and celebrating magnificent feats with barrels of mead amidst his fellow champions. He’s got an extensive past you can draw on, one of the best supporting casts in comics, the ability and motivation to head just about anywhere, he’s fun and sympathetic and fallible and probably the most unabashedly metal superhero of all time. He goes from Kirby cosmic to Aaron black death rock-opera, and even after all his years and titanic successes, I’d say he’s still underrated as one of Marvel’s best and most versatile characters.

As for endings, I don’t have much in mind: Hickman’s future for the universe as a whole shown in his Fantastic Four and Avengers works for me, the FF themselves get the future promised to them by God, Spidey I imagine eventually retires (if under protest) to live happily ever after with MJ, Punisher goes down in whatever’s the worst way you can think of, and as I’ve said before, Waid and Rodriguez’s The King In Red is and likely always will be what I default to as The Last Daredevil Story.

summary: In the sad wake of his passing, you've talked a bit about Steve Ditko. Any thoughts on the other definitive Spider-Man artist,...
question: In the sad wake of his passing, you've talked a bit about Steve Ditko. Any thoughts on the other definitive Spider-Man artist, John Romita?
answer: Romita is maybe the most GLAMOROUS superhero artist of them all - Ditko defined Spider-Man the character, Romita Spider-Man the icon. More than Kirby or Swan even, his work to me is probably the most archetypal sort of superhero art: bold, clean, powerful, lovely, direct. His stuff’s always a treat.

summary: I learned Spider-Man almost joined the Avengers twice in its initial lineup's days in 1963. Since the Avengers were SUPPOSED to...
question: I learned Spider-Man almost joined the Avengers twice in its initial lineup's days in 1963. Since the Avengers were SUPPOSED to be Marvel's biggest "solo" heroes teaming up a la the Justice League, how would a '63 Spidey membership and perhaps Hulk remaining with the team affect them in both a meta sense AND storytelling opportunities, as well as how it'd affect Spidey and Hulk themselves? For the sake of things, say everyone still leaves to allow the "Cap's Kooky Quartet" era to occur on time.
answer: Never happen - in-universe they were the big guns, but out of it they were the also-rans being grouped together. Spidey was too big for them.
